<p>Here, we have used the term "matrix" in its most general sense, recogniz=
ing that vectors and scalars are simply matrices with one column and one ro=
w respectively. Moreover, we have used bold letters to indicate vectors and=
 bold capital letters for matrices. This notation is used throughout.
</p><p>Notice that we could also talk about the derivative of a vector with=
 respect to a matrix, or any of the other unfilled cells in our table. Howe=
ver, these derivatives are most naturally organized in a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tensor" title=3D"Tensor">tensor</a> of rank higher t=
han 2, so that they do not fit neatly into a matrix. In the following three=
 sections we will define each one of these derivatives and relate them to o=
ther branches of mathematics. See the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Matrix_calculus#Layout_conventions">layout conventions</a> section for =
a more detailed table.
</p>
<h3><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Relation_to_other_derivatives">Relati=
on to other derivatives</span><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DMatrix_calculus&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"E=
dit section: Relation to other derivatives">edit</a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The matrix derivative is a convenient notation for keeping track of part=
ial derivatives for doing calculations. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Fr%C3%A9chet_derivative" title=3D"Fr=C3=A9chet derivative">Fr=C3=
=A9chet derivative</a> is the standard way in the setting of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_analysis" title=3D"Functional analysi=
s">functional analysis</a> to take derivatives with respect to vectors. In =
the case that a matrix function of a matrix is Fr=C3=A9chet differentiable,=
 the two derivatives will agree up to translation of notations. As is the c=
ase in general for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_derivat=
ive" title=3D"Partial derivative">partial derivatives</a>, some formulae ma=
y extend under weaker analytic conditions than the existence of the derivat=
ive as approximating linear mapping.
</p>
<h3><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Usages">Usages</span><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMatrix_calculus&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Usages">edit</a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Matrix calculus is used for deriving optimal stochastic estimators, ofte=
n involving the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange_mu=
ltipliers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lagrange multipliers">Lagrange mu=
ltipliers</a>. This includes the derivation of:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalman_filter" title=3D"Ka=
lman filter">Kalman filter</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiener_filter" title=3D"Wiener=
 filter">Wiener filter</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expectation-maximization_algor=
ithm#Gaussian_mixture" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Expectation-maximizat=
ion algorithm">Expectation-maximization algorithm for Gaussian mixture</a><=
/li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gradient_descent" title=3D"Gra=
dient descent">Gradient descent</a></li></ul>
<h2><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Notation">Notation</span><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMatrix_calculus&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Notation">edit</a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The vector and matrix derivatives presented in the sections to follow ta=
ke full advantage of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_notati=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Matrix notation">matrix notation</a>, us=
ing a single variable to represent a large number of variables. In what fol=
lows we will distinguish scalars, vectors and matrices by their typeface. W=
e will let <i>M</i>(<i>n</i>,<i>m</i>) denote the space of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real</a> <i>n=
=C3=97m</i> matrices with <i>n</i> rows and <i>m</i> columns.  Such matrice=
s will be denoted using bold capital letters: <b>A</b>, <b>X</b>, <b>Y</b>,=
 etc.  An element of <i>M</i>(<i>n</i>,1), that is, a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Column_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Column ve=
ctor">column vector</a>, is denoted with a boldface lowercase letter: <b>a<=
/b>, <b>x</b>, <b>y</b>, etc. An element of <i>M</i>(1,1) is a scalar, deno=
ted with lowercase italic typeface: <i>a</i>, <i>t</i>, <i>x</i>, etc. <b>X=
</b><sup>T</sup> denotes matrix <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tr=
anspose" title=3D"Transpose">transpose</a>, tr(<b>X</b>) is the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trace_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Trace (linea=
r algebra)">trace</a>, and det(<b>X</b>) or |<b>X</b>| is the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant" title=3D"Determinant">determinant<=
/a>. All functions are assumed to be of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Differentiability_class" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Differentiabi=
lity class">differentiability class</a> <i>C</i><sup>1</sup> unless otherwi=
se noted. Generally letters from the first half of the alphabet (a, b, c, .=
..) will be used to denote constants, and from the second half (t, x, y, ..=
.) to denote variables.
</p><p><b>NOTE</b>: As mentioned above, there are competing notations for l=
aying out systems of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_deriv=
ative" title=3D"Partial derivative">partial derivatives</a> in vectors and =
matrices, and no standard appears to be emerging yet.  The next two introdu=
ctory sections use the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_calc=
ulus#Layout_conventions">numerator layout convention</a> simply for the pur=
poses of convenience, to avoid overly complicating the discussion.  The sec=
tion after them discusses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_c=
alculus#Layout_conventions">layout conventions</a> in more detail.  It is i=
mportant to realize the following:
</p>
<ol><li>Despite the use of the terms "numerator layout" and "denominator la=
yout", there are actually more than two possible notational choices involve=
d.  The reason is that the choice of numerator vs. denominator (or in some =
situations, numerator vs. mixed) can be made independently for scalar-by-ve=
ctor, vector-by-scalar, vector-by-vector, and scalar-by-matrix derivatives,=
 and a number of authors mix and match their layout choices in various ways=
.</li>
<li>The choice of numerator layout in the introductory sections below does =
not imply that this is the "correct" or "superior" choice.  There are advan=
tages and disadvantages to the various layout types.  Serious mistakes can =
result from carelessly combining formulas written in different layouts, and=
 converting from one layout to another requires care to avoid errors.  As a=
 result, when working with existing formulas the best policy is probably to=
 identify whichever layout is used and maintain consistency with it, rather=
 than attempting to use the same layout in all situations.</li></ol>
<h3><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Alternatives">Alternatives</span><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMatrix_calculus&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Alternatives">edit</a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tensor_index_notation" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tensor index notation">tensor index notation</a>=
 with its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Einstein_summation" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Einstein summation">Einstein summation</a> conve=
ntion is very similar to the matrix calculus, except one writes only a sing=
le component at a time.  It has the advantage that one can easily manipulat=
e arbitrarily high rank tensors, whereas tensors of rank higher than two ar=
e quite unwieldy with matrix notation.  All of the work here can be done in=
 this notation without use of the single-variable matrix notation. However,=
 many problems in estimation theory and other areas of applied mathematics =
would result in too many indices to properly keep track of, pointing in fav=
or of matrix calculus in those areas.  Also, Einstein notation can be very =
useful in proving the identities presented here (see section on <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ricci_calculus#Differentiation" title=3D"Ricc=
i calculus">differentiation</a>) as an alternative to typical element notat=
ion, which can become cumbersome when the explicit sums are carried around.=
 Note that a matrix can be considered a tensor of rank two.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Derivatives_with_vectors">Derivatives=
 with vectors</span><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DMatrix_calculus&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Derivatives with vectors">edit</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></h2>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1033289096"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_calculus" tit=
le=3D"Vector calculus">Vector calculus</a></div>
<p>Because vectors are matrices with only one column, the simplest matrix d=
erivatives are vector derivatives.
</p><p>The notations developed here can accommodate the usual operations of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_calculus" title=3D"Vector =
calculus">vector calculus</a> by identifying the space <i>M</i>(<i>n</i>,1)=
 of <i>n</i>-vectors with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucl=
idean_space" title=3D"Euclidean space">Euclidean space</a> <b>R</b><sup><i>=
n</i></sup>, and the scalar <i>M</i>(1,1) is identified with <b>R</b>. The =
corresponding concept from vector calculus is indicated at the end of each =
subsection.
</p><p><b>NOTE</b>: The discussion in this section assumes the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_calculus#Layout_conventions">numerator =
layout convention</a> for pedagogical purposes.  Some authors use different=
 conventions.  The section on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matr=
ix_calculus#Layout_conventions">layout conventions</a> discusses this issue=
 in greater detail.  The identities given further down are presented in for=
ms that can be used in conjunction with all common layout conventions.
</p>
<h3><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Vector-by-scalar">Vector-by-scalar</s=
pan><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMatrix_calcu=
lus&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Vector-by-sca=
lar">edit</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
