<h2><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Identities">Identities</span><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMatrix_calculus&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Identities">edit</a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>As noted above, in general, the results of operations will be transposed=
 when switching between numerator-layout and denominator-layout notation.
</p><p>To help make sense of all the identities below, keep in mind the mos=
t important rules: the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_rule"=
 title=3D"Chain rule">chain rule</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Product_rule" title=3D"Product rule">product rule</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sum_rule_in_differentiation" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Sum rule in differentiation">sum rule</a>.  The sum rule appli=
es universally, and the product rule applies in most of the cases below, pr=
ovided that the order of matrix products is maintained, since matrix produc=
ts are not commutative.  The chain rule applies in some of the cases, but u=
nfortunately does <i>not</i> apply in matrix-by-scalar derivatives or scala=
r-by-matrix derivatives (in the latter case, mostly involving the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trace_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Trace (l=
inear algebra)">trace</a> operator applied to matrices).  In the latter cas=
e, the product rule can't quite be applied directly, either, but the equiva=
lent can be done with a bit more work using the differential identities.
</p><p>The following identities adopt the following conventions:
</p>
<ul><li>the scalars, a, b, c, d, and e are constant in respect of, and the =
scalars, u, and v are functions of one of x, <b>x</b>, or <b>X</b>;</li>
<li>the vectors, <b>a</b>, <b>b</b>, <b>c</b>, <b>d</b>, and <b>e</b> are c=
onstant in respect of, and the vectors, <b>u</b>, and <b>v</b> are function=
s of one of x, <b>x</b>, or <b>X</b>;</li>
<li>the matrices, <b>A</b>, <b>B</b>, <b>C</b>, <b>D</b>, and <b>E</b> are =
constant in respect of, and the matrices, <b>U</b> and <b>V</b> are functio=
ns of one of x, <b>x</b>, or <b>X</b>.</li></ul>
<h3><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Vector-by-vector_identities">Vector-b=
y-vector identities</span><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DMatrix_calculus&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit=
 section: Vector-by-vector identities">edit</a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>This is presented first because all of the operations that apply to vect=
or-by-vector differentiation apply directly to vector-by-scalar or scalar-b=
y-vector differentiation simply by reducing the appropriate vector in the n=
umerator or denominator to a scalar.
</p>
